comments.message: Need to make sure this certificate is in the container.

Hi Nicholas Yun,
Thanks for review.

Could you please provide more information about how to locate this certificate in the container?
It is helpful if have any document for reference about how to configure the external Flake server.
Thanks so much!

When we update this patch, we need to understand where this is being run. In this case, nginx.conf is run on two containers:
- flake-services
- flake-filter
your RootCA.crt is located in the azure server.  /data/nginx/conf/certs/RootCA.crt is the path in the azure server but not in the containers.

cmd to get names of containers: sudo docker ps
cmd to ssh into container: sudo docker exec -it <name of container> /bin/bash

Options:
1. You can move your /certs folder to within letsencrypt since its already being copied into the containers
2. You can add a volume mount within flake-azure.yml. Would need to add to both containers.
(flake-azure.yml information is in the Flake confluence page)

comments.message:
if we are gonna print that it failed for timeout then we should only catch that.
we can also catch general exception and print it out
except socket.timeout:
    flog.info("TCP Handler Timed Out. Closing Socket.")
    Client_SOCK.close()
except Exception as ex:
    flog.warning("TCP Handler Exception: {}".format(ex))
    Client_SOCK.close()

if client is doing something like
send_data()
sleep(50)
send_data()

then does the send_data() proceed?

Timeout is set to 120 seconds.
In this example, send_data proceeds.
When the client executes a close() it sends an empty buffer.
While the client is sleeping, the server is stuck on data = Client_SOCK.recv(buffer).
It either waits for a response from the client or times out.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix double delay

Now that the filter container is forwarding the incoming traffic
to the services container, we are actually applying tc rules on incoming
traffic.

With local services:
 I -> (iptables loss) -> (process) -> (tc delay + tc loss) -> O

With remote services:
 I -> (tc delay/2 + tc loss) -> (process) -> (tc delay/2 + tc loss) -> O

Resolves: FARM-4344
Change-Id: I1052bad33eb166db49c3f7577a9e11cf4c7c7337
Signed-off-by: Bertrand Roussel <broussel@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: Fix double delay

Can you add the dockerfile-pre-commit from https://cgit.legato/docker-images.git/tree/.pre-commit-config.yaml ?
And also some of the black/flake8/common stuff from https://cgit.legato/farm-control.git/tree/.pre-commit-config.yaml ?

Then run it with pre-commit run --files Dockerfile
To remove, that's bad practice apparently according to dockerlint
Why are you replacing this file? , the docker-entrypoint.sh is already present in the image.

I dont think it is present in nginx:1.14.2 also i needed to slightly modify:
if /usr/bin/find "/docker-entrypoint.d/" -mindepth 1 -maxdepth 1 -type f -print 2 because it has -q which was failing.
We'll need to figure out something for https, but we might end up copying that conf file locally.
Sounds good, I'll create a ticket to configure https for once the server is up.
Maybe add #!/bin/bash so editors know that it's a shell script (even though it's meant to be sourced)
I'm not sure I get that part, can you help my poor brain with a comment?

Actually, and with the risk of being annoying, could we build all this stuff in the image?
I mean the init script and tools.
That way we could push that image to a Docker registry and it could be run without this repository.
It would make the instantiation of the service easier since it would be standalone.

So we ignore nginx/ pretty much everything.. What we actually not ignore ? 
On the other hand, why we ignore nginx/html ?
Not everything, but yeah I guess most of this stuff is irrelevant now.
Removed most of this stuff, now that we are having everything in docker no need to have these ignores. as for what we are needing from nginx directory, conf/nginx.conf and public dir
